Data Sets

The biggest publicly accessible data databases and repositories in the world span petabytes (and even exabytes) of information, primarily hosted by government agencies, scientific research groups, and cloud-provider tech giants. 
The largest open repositories can be categorized by their specific scientific or structural focus:
🌍 Climate, Earth Science, and Space
NOAA National Centers for Environmental Information (NCEI): Holding over 40 petabytes of data, this is the world's largest archive of weather, oceanic, and atmospheric history.
NASA Earthdata: Coordinates tens of thousands of earth-science datasets, tracking satellite imagery, biosphere metrics, and planetary topography.
World Data Centre for Climate (WDCC): Managed by the German Climate Computing Centre, this hosts petabytes of raw climate simulation data accessible for open research. 

🧬 Genomics and Biological Sciences
NCBI / Sequence Read Archive (SRA): Operated by the U.S. National Institutes of Health, the SRA holds petabytes of raw high-throughput DNA/RNA sequencing data from thousands of organisms worldwide.
CERN Open Data Portal: Shares more than a petabyte of complex particle physics data generated from the Large Hadron Collider experiments. 
💻 Web Crawls and Machine Learning
Common Crawl: A non-profit that compiles massive multi-petabyte datasets containing billions of web pages collected over years of scanning the internet. It is the foundation for many large AI models.
Google Dataset Search & Data Commons: Google acts as a massive indexing layer mapping out thousands of public repositories. Its Data Commons project unifies statistics from the UN, CDC, and world governments into a single queryable format. 
📊 Global Infrastructure Cloud Registries
AWS Registry of Open Data: Amazon hosts massive public datasets for free. This allows researchers to query genomic data, satellite grids, and transport maps using cloud tools without downloading them.
Google BigQuery Public Datasets: A giant analytical warehouse offering immediate SQL access to crypto transaction histories, public health records, and global weather histories. 
🏛️ Demographics and Government Data
Data.gov & Eurostat: Data.gov serves as the central clearinghouse for over 250,000 free datasets from the U.S. government. Eurostat handles comparable volumes for European Union socio-economic data.
World Bank Open Data: The definitive hub for macro-economic, financial, and population development indicators covering almost every country. HMDA (Home Mortgage Disclosure Act) Data - https://ffiec.cfpb.gov/data-publication/2024
